hints_latex:
An investment with initial value $A_0$ compounded quarterly at interest
rate $r$ (per year) will grow to a value of

\begin{align*}
A(t)=A_0(1+r/4)^{4t}
\end{align*} after a time $t$ in years.

sols_latex:
Using the discrete compound interest formula with 4 compounds per year,
we know that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \$12000=\$10000(1+0.12/4)^{4t},
\end{align*}

where \emph{t} is the time in years required for the
\textbackslash{}\$10 000 investment to grow to \textbackslash{}\$12 000.
We want to solve for \emph{t}. Dividing both sides by
\textbackslash{}\$10000,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 1.2=(1+0.03)^{4t}.
\end{align*}

Taking the logarithm of both sides and simplifying,

\begin{align*}
\ln(1.2)= \ln\left(1.03^{4t}\right) = 4t \ln\left(1.03\right)
\end{align*}

Hence, the investment will take

\begin{align*}
t= \frac{\ln(1.2)}{4\ln(1.03)}
\end{align*}

years to grow to \textbackslash{}\$12000.

''A calculator would tell you that \emph{t} is about 1.54 years.''
